          "idea": "**The Idea:** There's a calculable threshold beyond which helping someone adopt new tools becomes net-negative for both parties. **V's Framing:** \"Over the years I've developed an intuition for how much I can help someone and more importantly how much help is even worth offering because sometimes it just ends up being more.\" **Why This Is Interesting:** - Maps to product design: Features can hurt adoption if they require too much system-change - Suggests a \"help calculus\" that factors in the helper's cost, not just the recipient's benefit - The phrase \"more\" (trailing off) implies the cost is hard to articulate but viscerally felt **Implication for Calendly:** Their SMB therapist market may have a \"help threshold\" that determines product design boundaries. ---",
